Solution — Exercise 02: GDB Variables
========================================

Step 1: Load and break at main
  gdb ./target
  (gdb) break main
  (gdb) run
  → stops at the first line of main

Step 2: Step to after 'key' is initialized
  (gdb) next
  → int key = 0 executes
  (gdb) print key
  → $1 = 0

Step 3: Overwrite the variable
  (gdb) set variable key = 0x1337
  (gdb) print key
  → $2 = 4919   (which is 0x1337)

Step 4: Resume
  (gdb) continue
  → Key is: 0
  → [SUCCESS] You changed the key. Variables bend to your will.

Why it matters:
  GDB can read and write any variable in a running process.
  Combined with breakpoints, this gives you complete control
  over a program's state — exactly what you need for debugging
  and for the exploitation exercises ahead.
